:YeastPathways_YEAST-SALV-PYRMID-DNTP
        a                   owl:NamedIndividual , obo:GO_0043099 ;
        rdfs:comment        "The deoxynucleotides required for DNA synthesis can either be made de novo, or they can be salvaged from endogenous degradation processes |CITS: 10501935||CITS: 2189783|. If the required substrates are available, the salvage pathways of pyrimidine deoxyribonucleotides are preferred over de novo synthesis pathways for pyrimidine biosynthesis |CITS:12111094|. As with many of the metabolic pathways of S. cerevisiae, the pathways for the salvage of pyrimidine deoxyribonucleotides are regulated by a variety of processes, including transcription regulation |CITS: 11292850||CITS: 12570998|. Saccharomyces cerevisiae contains three enzymes (Urk1p, Urh1p, and Cdd1p) that are able to salvage deoxycytidine in vitro |CITS: 12111094|. However of these three enzymes, only Urk1p and Urh1p have been shown to metabolize deoxycytidine in vivo |CITS: 12111094|. In vitro Cdd1p has been shown to deaminate deoxycytidine to form deoxyuridine, however the biological significance of this is doubtful |CITS:10501935||CITS:12111094|. Evidence that Cdd1p is not important for deoxypyrimidine salvage comes from the observation that fyc1 urh1 urk1 triple mutants are resistant to 5-fluorodeoxycytidine, indicating that these cells are not able to metabolize deoxycytidine |CITS:12111094|. Also deoxyuridine does not allow growth of ura- strains, indicating that deoxyuridine cannot be utilized as a sole source of pyrimidines in S. cerevisiae |CITS:12111094|." ;
        rdfs:label          "salvage pathways of pyrimidine deoxyribonucleotides" ;
        layout:x            "349.375" ;
        layout:y            "21" ;
        dc:contributor      "GOC:sgd_curators" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-5472-917X" ;
        dc:date             "2024-07-15" ;
        pav:providedBy      "http://www.yeastgenome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "YeastPathways_YEAST-SALV-PYRMID-DNTP" ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

